sentences: His nascent singing career was put on hold, however, by the outbreak of World War I in 1914, during which he served with the Italian armed forces reaching the rank of captain and emerged as one of Italy's most decorated soldiers.
Four months later, on 3 January 1920, he scored another success, at the Teatro Costanzi in Rome, this time performing under his own name opposite Rosina Storchio and Ezio Pinza in Massenet's Manon.
A highlight of his Milan seasons occurred in 1929 when he was chosen to sing  Arnoldo in La Scala's centenary production of Rossini's Guglielmo Tell.
He was also a leading tenor at the New York Metropolitan Opera from 1923 to 1933, appearing there in a total of 307 performances.
Lauri-Volpi's most notable appearances outside Italy also included two seasons at the Royal Opera House, Covent Garden—in 1925 and 1936.
His voice began to show consequent signs of wear in the 1940s, losing homogeneity.
His thrilling top notes remained remarkably intact, however, right through until the 1950s.
His last public performance in a full opera came in 1959, as Manrico, in a production of Verdi's Il Trovatore staged at Rome.
In 1947, he recorded in Italy a series of extended scenes from Rigoletto.
Later, in the 1950s, he participated in the recording of some complete operas that do not capture his voice at anywhere like its peak.
La bohème, Il trovatore and Luisa Miller (all made in 1951);
Il trovatore and La favorita (both made in 1954, both live); and
Gli Ugonotti (1955).
In addition, there is a live recording of Il trovatore from Naples in 1951, in which he is partnered by Maria Callas, under the baton of Tullio Serafin.
In 1974, aged 81, Lauri-Volpi released a final operatic recital record; but this particular LP has novelty value only.
There are bits of newsreel footage of him performing on stage, too, and he appeared in the 1936 Italian film La Canzone del Sole, playing himself.
Voci Parallele (Ricordi, Napoli, 1955);
L'Equivoco, Cosi è, e non vi pare (Corbaccio, Milano, 1938); and
Aviso Aperto, (Corbaccio, Milano, 1953)

The war over, he made a successful operatic debut as Arturo in Bellini's I Puritani in Viterbo, Italy, on 2 September 1919—performing under the name Giacomo Rubini, after Bellini's favorite tenor, Giovanni Battista Rubini.

sentences: Giacomo Lauri-Volpi (11 December 1892 – 17 March 1979) was an Italian tenor with a lyric voice of exceptional range and technical facility.
He performed throughout Europe and the Americas in a top-class career that spanned 40 years.
Four months later, on 3 January 1920, he scored another success, at the Teatro Costanzi in Rome, this time performing under his own name opposite Rosina Storchio and Ezio Pinza in Massenet's Manon.

In the process, he cemented his position as one of the supreme opera singers of the 20th century, even though he faced stiff competition from a remarkable crop of rival Mediterranean tenors during his prime in the 1925-1940 period.
During the 1920s and 1930s, Lauri-Volpi made a number of 78-rpm recordings of operatic arias and duets for the following companies: Fonotipia, Brunswick, Victor and, finally, HMV.
